Use the binge.csv dataset to assess the difference in food intake level for mice in 4 different genotypes.

binge <- read_csv("binge.csv")

A. Clearly state your statistical hypotheses and decide on alpha

Knowing nothing about the habits or genotypes of binge eating mice, I would first look at the data.

# Look at the variance within each group
binge %>% 
  group_by(Genotype) %>% 
  summarise(Variance = var(Intake))

The variances make me wonder, but I don’t really know how much difference is too much at this point, so I just mention it and set it aside for now.

# I really, really like this! 
binge_sum <- binge %>% 
  group_by(Genotype) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(Intake, na.rm = TRUE),
          n = n(),
          SD = sd(Intake, na.rm = TRUE),
          lower = mean - SD,
          upper = mean + SD)

binge_sum

With four genotype groups, A, B, C, and D, I will just assume that these mice are all the same, except for the difference in one gene/allele. Therefore:

H0: \(\bar{A}\) = \(\bar{B}\) = \(\bar{C}\) = \(\bar{D}\)

After reviewing some descriptive statistics I see that there is difference in the amount of variance within the groups, with var(A) twice that of var(D).

Next, I’ll check if the distribution is normal within groups:

binge %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sample=Intake))+
  geom_qq()+
  geom_qq_line() +
  facet_wrap(~Genotype, ncol = 4) +
  theme_ipsum_ps() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-1.5, 0, 1.5)) +
  labs(title="QQ Plots of Binge Eating Mice",
       subtitle="grouped by genotype",
       x = "theoretical quantile",
       y = "sample of quantile")

For such a small number of samples, this is much more ‘normal’ than I expected, so I’ll continue, assuming normality has been met.

It is possible that there may not be a statistical difference between all of the groups, but one or more group may be statistically different to one or more others in the group. I’m not certain of the proper way to describe this, but I would at least state that:

H1: \(\bar{A}\) <> \(\bar{B}\) <> \(\bar{C}\) <> \(\bar{D}\)

I also see that we have a small number of samples from each group. I want the power of my test to be higher, and without being able to increase the sample size, I will set the threshold of rejecting the null hypothesis to be higher, so I arbitrarily set alpha as 0.01.

B. Run the test and interpret the ANOVA output

# Intake, dependent on Genotype
fit <- lm(Intake ~ Genotype,
          data = binge)

anova(fit)

So there are significant difference between groups…

The ANOVA table indicates that there is a significant difference in the means of the four groups, with a very low p-value. This indicates that the means of the four groups are different, but does not tell us which one is ‘more different’ or if there are any two groups that are by themselves not significantly different. It’s not Thanksgiving yet, but it certainly is time for Tukey.

C. If it is appropriate, run a Tukey’s HSD post-hoc analysis to determine which group differs. Interpret the output.

tidy(TukeyHSD(aov(fit)))

With these results we can see that groups A and C are the groups with the greatest (and statistically significant) difference between their means.

There was no statistically significant difference in the means of groups B-C (P=0.250), and B-D (P=0.119).

There was a marginally significant difference in the means of groups A-D (P=0.0745).

There was a statistically significant difference in the means of groups A-B (P<0.001), A-C (P<0.0001), and C-D (P<0.001).

With such small sample sizes, though, we have to be aware of the chance that this may not be representative of a larger group/population.

You might have heard of the Bechdel’s test where a movie passes if it:

  1. has at least two women in it, who
  2. talk to each other, about
  3. something besides a man

I recently stumbled on a (old) interesting article analyzing whether the number of words spoken by male and female characters in movies was balanced or not. To see their whole analysis, head to the pudding.

C. Let’s say we are interested in whether the sum of words spoken by male characters equals that of female characters. State your statistical hypotheses and alpha.

Note that the sum implies that we will analyze count data. A t-test is not appropriate for count data.

With the assumption of not having any special knowledge, we would state:

H0: words spoken by masculine character = words spoken by feminine character

To analyze this, we would be comparing the proportion of words spoken by gender. In the case of this particular movie, I have prior knowledge of this film and know that the title character is a feminine character, so based on this I would expect there to be more words spoken by feminine characters than masculine characters.

H1: words spoken by masculine character < words spoken by feminine character

I have no reason not to set alpha at 0.05, but it is arbitrary.

D. For your movie dataset, sum up the number of words spoken by males and by females.

words <- amelie %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarise(word_count = sum(words))

words

E. What type of test is this? How do you know?

This is discrete data, a count of words in which each word is categorized as being spoken by a feminine or masculine character. This is a comparison of proportions between two groups.

In this case, we actually know the P, or the whole population of words in this movie.

Since this is a binomial choice between a feminine or masculine character, there really aren’t two categories to compare (unless there was a non-binary gender character recorded in the dataset). The words spoken by masculine characters are equal to the total number of words minus the words spoken by feminine characters. Therefore, this should be analyzed with a one-proportion z-test.

F. Check the assumptions of this test.

The number of words spoken is not a sample of the entire population, but rather is the entire population, so there is no need to analyze whether the samples were taken randomly or to assess the number of samples. The total number of words is 6980, so this is not a small population.

G. Run the test and interpret the output

total_words <- sum(words$word_count)

fem_words <- words %>% filter(gender == "f")
fem_words <- fem_words$word_count

prop.test(x = fem_words, 
          n = total_words, 
          p = 0.5,
          alternative = "greater")
## 
##  1-sample proportions test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  fem_words out of total_words, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 90.093, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true p is greater than 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5470048 1.0000000
## sample estimates:
##         p 
## 0.5568768

In this movie, the number of words spoken by a feminine character (n=3887) was greater than those spoken by a masculine character (n=3093) and the difference was statistically significant (P=<0.0001).

Problem 3 – Movie genre

genre_movies.csv is a pared down dataset of the movies dataset we used above.

Use the genre_movies dataset to assess the association between words spoken by each gender within each genre of movie. Follow all steps of hypothesis testing to run a contingency table test (test of independence) for these data.

A. Write out your statistical hypotheses and alpha

Armed with some background in watching movies and admitting to peeking at the data for way too long instead of working on the actual homework, I was surprised to see that the movie I picked was somewhat of an exception. Still, trying to remember my previous less-biased state, I would have suggested the following hypotheses:

H0: words spoken by masculine character = words spoken by feminine character across all genres.

H1: words spoken by masculine character > words spoken by feminine character in the genre “Action.”

H2: words spoken by masculine character < words spoken by feminine character in the genre “Romance.”

This is not some sterotypical view, but just what I glean from what I hear when I’m busy on homework all weekend and my wife takes the opportunity to be a Genotype C house mouse and binges Netflix for a few hours on a Sunday afternoon.
